fields.name: Hifi Shades Of Grey
fields.description:
Hot on the heels of their releases on Nu Groove and Refuge Recordings Acid Jerks are back once again with another EP of jackin' traxx.

It's their first for Local Talk and we are, of course both proud and honoured to release 'Hifi Shades Of Grey'. The Acid Jerks sound is tried and tested to perfection by now and their fans won't be disappointed listening to this EP for sure.

First up is 'Shades Of Grey', a proper builder with its haunting strings, setting the tone perfectly. Then we have 'Wheels Of Fortune', a track with that raw Chicago vibe. Warehouse soul anyone? Both 'Rise Up' and 'Ace Of Spade' are tracks infused with that and equal parts of old-school and bounce.

Acid Jerks makes music that is impossible to ignore, it's a fact.

fields.name: Hip Hop / g'Head
fields.description:
When it comes to breathing new life into classic cuts Joseph Caserta is as good as it gets, proven many times on his imprint BridgeBoots.

Making punchy and jackin' house, sounding like it's been dipped in some secret sauce is another trick of his.

The first track on his Local Talk debut, Hip Hop, comes in two flavours with the special sauce added on top.
Both the Rap Mix and the Haus Dub got swinging drums and a meaty, stabby chord that keeps the energy tight. g'Head' is a punchy and bumpy house jacker that takes a hold of you and doesn't let go.

fields.name: 1990's​​​-​​​ISH (Part 2)
fields.description:
Here's the second part of our 1990-ISH, a compilation reminiscent of 90's house music. Part two is full of energy and drive and seductive filled with house retro-futurism.

Plenty of classics included from Dirtytwo, Art Of Tones, Chesus, Willie Graff & Tuccillo, DJ Steaw and more.

fields.name: 1990's​-​ISH (Part 1)
fields.description:
The new ISH compilation evokes memories of those sweaty basements parties circa 1990-ish, when clubbers would go crazy for tunes played in the club. A compilation with plenty of bumpin' basslines, razor sharp hihats and a lot of 90s New York percussion.
Twelve tracks with sounds inspired from Burrell Brothers, Red Zone-era David Morales and more.

What else do you need?

fields.name: Close To The Source (FT. Ricoh)
fields.description:
Dan Tenor-City and Tom Funk debuts on Local Talk with Close To The Source featuring Ricoh, a true nightlife veteran from the Paradise Garage to Body & Soul to 718 Sessions and beyond.

Close To The Source is a deep cut that combines the raw 70s disco and funk feel and 80s proto house. A tune that is trippy & pacey in all the right places. On remix duties French veteran Art Of Tones adds his classic signature bump and the P.P.A. Dub is a deliciously deep journey and shows yet another side of the exceptional original.

fields.name: Jack​-​Ish
fields.description:
Do You Know Jack?

The fourth release in Local Talk series is called Jack-Ish.
Since the very beginning of Local Talk we've made sure there's been a bit of jack present in the tunes we release.

If you want your tunes sweaty, funked-up mixed with killer vintage drum machine rhythms bonanza then look no further, this compilation is for you.
Essential for fans of straight up unadulterated club traxxxx.

fields.name: Massilia
fields.description:
Local Talk are proud to welcome a new member to the family, French-born, Berlin-based producer Maytra.

Maytra makes his debut on Local Talk with Massilia. We first noticed this young aspiring producer after listening to his music on Visions Recordings.

These four tracks on this EP are very unique takes on dance music from a producer that is just starting in what we believe is a long journey in house music. He's showcasing his ability to seamlessly blend diverse influences and sounds.

All tracks are uplifting and Maytra knows a thing or two about blending jazz, broken beat, soul and deep house in his productions. Taking inspiration from producers such as Kyle Hall and Hannah and adds his own personal twist makes this a release we proud to present to you all.

fields.name: Let It Go
fields.description:
French producer, musician and DJ, Thomas Arroyo aka Laroye has over the last couple of years been dropping musical releases in all the rights places, Atjazz Record Company, Vision Recordings, Ocha Records and Freerange Records to drop a few names! It's now time for his long-awaited album and Local Talk are extremely proud to present 'Let It Go'.


From his studio in Brighton where he resides nowadays, Laroye has produced eight highly musical compositions that will appeal to a wide audience of house heads as well as the jazz, soul, and funk communities. The album offers everything from vocal soul /boogie jams like 'Beauty in motion' and 'Grateful' to the deep vocal house of 'Let it go' to jazz-funk with a strong rare groove feel on 'People out there' plus some house cuts for the clubs!

'Let It Go' is eight solid tracks that you'll want to play over and over and over. Local Talk coming at us once again with high quality dance music at its very best.

fields.name: Sum Luv / Styrax (Zed Bias Remixes)
fields.description:
Now, this release is really special. Warsaw's finest producer, envee (yes spelled in lower case) has been around the block since the early 2000s and is arguably Poland's #1 producer of underground dance music...with soul.

With a sound that often leans towards the UK underground, we thought that we should enlist one of envee's (and our) fave producers to remix his new Local Talk release; Manchester's finest Zed Bias.

We asked Zed to give us that deep, soulful 2-Step rub but with a slight jazz edge and boy did he deliver. Not only did he remix one of the tracks, he got so inspired and remixed both tracks...don!
It's proper UK deep UK 2-step / garage that will work in any (!) decent club. Yup it's that good.

We of course need to mention the original mixes from envee himself.
Sum Luv is a warm and melodic hip hop / soul jam with a slight Dilla(ish) backbeat. A proper tune!

Styrax sounds like a killer jazz-funk banger straight out the Bugz In The Attic playbook with jazzy Rhodes, breakbeats, big strings, and a bad bassline. West London meets Wars aw...bam!!

fields.name: Local Talk - 13 Years Later (Part 2)
fields.description:
We've now been at this since 2010 and over the years we've really tried to deliver the kind of house music (and beyond) that we would play, listen and dance to ourselves.   We really tried to avoid the dangerous traps of following trends which in the long run can water down labels to just a music portal instead of a music brand with character. Basically, we aim to deliver our own musical personality via artists and producers that we love and respect. To sum things up, we are proud to present our second label compilation, Local Talk - 13 Years Later.
 
In part two of our 13 Years Later compilation we reached out to both regular in-house producers as well as some brand new friends on the house scene.   As always, we try and aim for a wide spectrum of styles and you'll hear everything from classic house, deep house, soulful house, dub and hip hop from some of our fave producers like Wipe The Needle, James L'Estraunge Orchestra, Damon Frost.

We also included producers like Glenn Davis, Rico Herrera, Aurelius and Caserta which we believe is doing exciting music and should be heard by many more.   

We sincerely hope you will enjoy this selection of dance MUSIC as much as we do and that there's something for everyone on our compilation.
